    "remarks": {
      "sha256": "f8e0d85ab3dd683fcd5fb38a8fa638228424b02b7b39cff7a97e92fe07bb7976",
      "source_region": "div.problem-additional-text",
      "text": "Erd\\H{o}s wrote he could prove this for $\\epsilon=1/2$."
    },
    "statement": {
      "sha256": "5634010cc989b0556eb3cab1aea61814afd7adfa60601a8501a4581bc2bd0d98",
      "source_region": "div#content",
      "text": "Is it true that for every $\\epsilon,\\eta>0$ there exists a $k$ such that the density of $n$ for which\\[P(n(n+1)\\cdots(n+k))>n^{1-\\epsilon}\\]is at least $1-\\eta$ (where $P(m)$ is the greatest prime divisor of $m$)?"
    }
  },
